<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12007m"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12007m">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12007m"> 7(m)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> I esteem it vain / <font face="wake">C</font> solecism!</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">108-9 <font color="green">[Christophe quotes a letter to the editor by Andr&eacute; Gide defending certain changes the French language undergoes]</font>: <mark>J&apos;estime qu&apos;il est vain</mark>, qu&apos;il est dangereux, de se cramponner &agrave; des tournures et &agrave; des significations tomb&eacute;es en d&eacute;su&eacute;tude, et que c&eacute;der un peu permet de r&eacute;sister beaucoup. Consid&eacute;rez l&apos;aventure du subjonctif: quand la r&egrave;gle <font color="green">[108]</font> est trop incommode, on passe outre. L&apos;enfant dit: <i>tu voulais que je vienne</i>, ou: <i>que j&apos;aille</i>, et il a raison. Il sait bien qu&apos;en disant: <i>tu voulais que je vinsse</i>, ou: <i>que j&apos;allasse</i>, ainsi que son ma&icirc;tre, hier encore, le lui enseignait, il va se faire rire au nez par ses camarades, ce qui lui para&icirc;t beaucoup plus grave que de commettre un <mark>sol&eacute;cisme</mark>. <br><font color="green">[I believe it is useless, even dangerous, to hang on to expressions and meanings that are in the process of disappearing, we have to give way in order to put up a better form of resistance. Think of the subjunctive: when the rules are too strict, one tries something else. A child says: <i>tu voulais que je vienne</i>, or: <i>que j&apos;aille</i> and it is right. He knows very well that in saying <i>tu voulais que je vinsse</i>, ou: <i>que j&apos;allasse</i>, like his schoolmaster taught him only yesterday, he is going to be made fun of by his comrades, which for him is much more serious than to commit a solecism.]</font> <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 108-9</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
